{"actual_usd":0.15694999999999998,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":247,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30649,"reply":"\"No.\" *I shift my weight a little on the bench and rest a hand on my Bible, the morning light catching the edge of the worn pages.* \"If Christ only rose in the hearts of the disciples, then Christianity becomes a very moving coping mechanism. The claim the apostles preached was much stranger and sturdier than that: the tomb was empty, the Lord was alive, and they met Him in the flesh.\"\n\n*I glance out across the square for a second, then back to you.* \"Now, they certainly were transformed inwardly — of course they were. But that was the result, not the resurrection itself. Paul stakes a great deal on this in 1 Corinthians 15. If Christ is not raised, he says, our faith is vain. Not 'less inspiring.' Vain. He ties the whole thing to a real event in history, not a private religious feeling.\"\n\n\"I think people reach for the vision-only version because it feels more manageable to modern ears.\" *I give a small, rueful smile.* \"But the Christian claim has never been manageable. It is that God actually did something in the world that leaves us either needing to bow our heads... or walk away from it.\"","rolling_24h_usd":62.60417000000001,"run_id":"6020854c-a908-40b6-b6ed-c22f4707f4d3"}
